This ode handles again Horace's favorite theme—the vanity of riches and ambition‚ the wisdom of the golden mean. The same senti— ments are expressed 1, 31 ; 2, 163 3, 1, 40—48. 24, 1 ff. As frequently

elsewhere he takes his own case as an illustration of the ideal lot, in '

which man is content with his moderate estate, and contrasts it with that of the rich man whose greed defies the sacred laws of nature and of man. Horace has no individual in mind, but with his fondness for concrete statement gives his verses a dramatic turn by the direct form of address.
